# `DataGrid` selected item does not change when I select a different row

I'm not sure if this is the right place to ask this, but I can't seem to find anything on Stack Overflow. In short, I have a `DataGrid` that's bound to an `ObservableCollection` of a custom class I've written called `Coordinate`. When I populate the collection by adding rows in the data grid, the collection gets updated correctly. However, when I click around to select different rows (e.g. to update their content), my binding to the grid's `SelectedItem` does not seem to change.

## 1. Implementations

### a. `DataGrid` implementation

```xaml
<DataGrid x:Name="CoordinatesData"
                 ItemsSource="{Binding Coordinates}"
                 SelectedItem="{Binding SelectedCoordinate}"
                 AutoGenerateColumns="False"
                 CanUserAddRows="True"
                 CanUserReorderColumns="False"
                 CanUserSortColumns="False"
                 CanUserResizeColumns="False">
    <DataGrid.Columns>
        <DataGridTextColumn Header="Xs" Binding="{Binding X}" />
        <DataGridTextColumn Header="Ys" Binding="{Binding Y}" />
    </DataGrid.Columns>
</DataGrid>
```

### b. Viewmodel implementation

```csharp
public class CoordinatesViewmodel : ...
{
    ...
    private ObservableCollection<Coordinate<double, double>> _coordinates = new ObservableCollection<Coordinate<double, double>>();
    private Coordinate<double, double> _selectedCoordinate = null;
    ...
    public ObservableCollection<Coordinate<double, double>> Coordinates
    {
        get => _coordinates;
        set => _coordinates = value;
    }
    public Coordinate<double, double>> SelectedCoordinate
    {
        get => _selectedCoordinate;
        set => _selectedCoordinate = value;
    }
    ...
}
```

### c. `Coordinate<T, U>` implementation

```csharp
public class Coordinate<T, U> : IComparable<Coordinate<T, U>>, IEquatable<Coordinate<T, U>>
    where T : IComparable<T>, IEquatable<T>
    where U : IComparable<U>, IEquatable<U>
{
    public Coordinate() { }
    public Coordinate(T x, U y)
    {
        X = x;
        Y = y;
    }

    public T X { get; set; }
    public U Y { get; set; }

    public override string ToString() => $"({X}, {Y})";

    public int CompareTo(Coordinate<T, U> other)
    {
        if (!(other is null) && other is Coordinate<T, U> cObj)
        {
            var result = X.CompareTo(cObj.X) == 0
                            ? Y.CompareTo(cObj.Y)
                            : X.CompareTo(cObj.X);
            return result;
        }
        return 1;
    }

    public bool Equals(Coordinate<T, U> other)
        => ReferenceEquals(this, other);

    public override bool Equals(object obj)
        => obj is Coordinate<T, U> cObj && Equals(cObj);

    public override int GetHashCode()
        => HashCode.Combine(X, Y);

    public static bool operator ==(Coordinate<T, U> left, Coordinate<T, U> right)
        => left?.CompareTo(right) == 0;

    public static bool operator !=(Coordinate<T, U> left, Coordinate<T, U> right)
        => !(left == right);

    public static bool operator <(Coordinate<T, U> left, Coordinate<T, U> right)
        => left?.CompareTo(right) < 0;

    public static bool operator >(Coordinate<T, U> left, Coordinate<T, U> right)
        => left?.CompareTo(right) > 0;

    public static bool operator <=(Coordinate<T, U> left, Coordinate<T, U> right)
        => left?.CompareTo(right) <= 0;

    public static bool operator >=(Coordinate<T, U> left, Coordinate<T, U> right)
        => left?.CompareTo(right) >= 0;
}
```

## 2. Observations

I thought that the `SelectedItem` property would automatically take care of selection changes and whatnot, but what I've noticed is that I only get into the setter when the first row of the `DataGrid` is added to the collection. After that, I can keep adding new rows but when I then select one of the previous rows, my `SelectedItem` property does not update.

What could be the issue here?
